example.p:
A typical element of U can be described parametrically as
 \begin{bmatrix} x \amp x + y \\ 0 \amp y \end{bmatrix} .
The parameters x,y have no further dependence relation between them,
so they each have an associated basis vector:

	U = \Span\left\{
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
	\right\}
.

To be an element of \orthogcmp{U},
an arbitrary element
 B = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix} 
of \matrixring_{2 \times 2} (\R) must be orthogonal to each of the basis vectors A_1,A_2 for U above.
We have


		\inprod{B}{A_1} \amp = \trace(\utrans{A}_1 B) \amp
		\inprod{B}{A_2} \amp = \trace(\utrans{A}_2 B)

		\amp = \trace\left(
			\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
			\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}
		\right)
		\amp
		\amp = \trace\left(
			\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
			\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}
		\right)

		\amp = \trace \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ a \amp b \end{bmatrix}
		\amp
		\amp = \trace \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ a + c \amp b + d \end{bmatrix}

		\amp = a + b \text{,}
		\amp
		\amp = b + d \text{.}


For orthogonality, we need both of these results to be zero,
leading to homogeneous system

	\left\{
		\begin{array}{cc}
			a + b \amp = 0, \\
			b + d \amp = 0.
		\end{array}
	\right.

Since parameter b appears in both equations,
we choose to leave that free, and then have  a = d = -b .
Parameter c does not appear in the system,
hence must be free as well.
So a typical element of \orthogcmp{U} can be described parametrically as
 \left[\begin{array}{rr} -b \amp b \\ c \amp -b \end{array}\right] ,
leading to

	\orthogcmp{U} = \Span\left\{
		\left[\begin{array}{rr} -1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{array}\right],
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
	\right\}
.

Let \uvec{w}_1,\uvec{w}_2,\uvec{w}_3,\uvec{w}_4 represent the four initial basis vectors above.
Set \uvec{e}_1 = \uvec{w}_1,
and compute


		\inprod{\uvec{w}_2}{\uvec{e}_1}
		= \dotprod{\uvec{w}_2}{\uvec{e}_1}
		= 1 - 1 - \ci^2 - \ci^2
		= 2 \text{,}


		\norm{\uvec{e}_1}^2
		= \dotprod{\uvec{e}_1}{\uvec{e}_1}
		= 1 + 1 - \ci^2 - \ci^2
		= 4

.

Let's revisit ,
where we considered subspace

	U = \Span\left\{
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
	\right\}

of V = \matrixring_{2 \times 2}(\R).
(We equip V with the standard inner product \inprod{A}{B} = \trace (\utrans{B} A).)

The basis for U can be enlarged into a basis for V by including a couple of standard basis vectors:

	\basisfont{B}_0 = \left\{
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
	\right\}
.
We won't go through all the calculations this time,
but applying the
 process
to \basisfont{B}_0
(and clearing fractions along the way)
results in orthogonal basis

	\basisfont{B} = \left\{
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\left[\begin{array}{rc} -1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 2 \end{array}\right],
		\left[\begin{array}{rc} -1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{array}\right],
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
	\right\}
.
As \dim U was 2 in the first place,
the first two vectors in \basisfont{B} form a basis for U.
And as the entire basis \basisfont{B} is an orthogonal set,
the last two vectors in \basisfont{B} must form a basis for \orthogcmp{U}.
That is, we can split \basisfont{B} in two to obtain an orthogonal basis for each of U,\orthogcmp{U}:

	\basisfont{B}_U \amp = \left\{
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\left[\begin{array}{rc} -1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 2 \end{array}\right]
	\right\} \text{,}
	\amp
	\basisfont{B}_{\orthogcmp{U}} \amp = \left\{
		\left[\begin{array}{rc} -1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{array}\right],
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
	\right\}
.

Consider the space V = C[0,1] of all continuous functions defined on the interval 0 \le x \le 1, equipped with the inner product \inprod{f}{g} = \integral{0}{1}{f(x) g(x)}{x} . Then the infinite set
S = \bigl\{ \sin (2 \pi x), \cos (2 \pi x), \sin (4 \pi x), \cos (4 \pi x), \dotsc, \sin (2 \pi n x), \cos (2 \pi n x), \dotsc \bigr\}
is an infinite orthogonal set in V.

To verify this,
assume m,n are integers with m \neq n.
Setting k = m - n and K = m + n for convenience,
we could calculate


		\inprod{\sin (2 \pi m x)}{\sin (2 \pi n x)}
		= \frac{K \sin (2 \pi k) - k \sin (2 \pi K)}
		  {4 \pi k K}
		  \text{,}


		\inprod{\cos (2 \pi m x)}{\cos (2 \pi n x)}
		= \frac{K \sin (2 \pi k) + k \sin (2 \pi K)}
		  {4 \pi k K}
		  \text{,}


		\inprod{\sin (2 \pi m x)}{\cos (2 \pi n x)}
		= \frac{2 m - K \cos (2 \pi k) - k \cos (2 \pi K)}
		  {4 \pi k K}
		  \text{,}


		\inprod{\sin (2 \pi n x)}{\cos (2 \pi n x)}
		= \frac{1 - \cos^2 (2 \pi n)}{4 \pi n}
		  \text{.}


The first two expressions evaluate to zero because sine evaluates to zero at every integer multiple of 2 \pi.
On the other hand, cosine evaluates to one at every integer multiple of 2 \pi,
so the numerator of the third expression becomes
 2 m - K - k = 2 m - (m + n) - (m - n)  = 0 ,
and the numerator of the fourth expression also obviously evaluates to zero.
